  <span id="freeText2831201033819695616" style="display:none">This is one of those highly praised novels that I've been meaning to read for more than a decade, and this holiday break I finally made time for it. <br /><br /><i>Gilead</i> is told in stream-of-consciousness style, following the thoughts and reflections of the small-town reverend John Ames, who has learned he has a heart condition and doesn't have long to live. John tells his story in the form of a letter to his young son, and the reader hears all kinds of reminsiscences from his long life, and also learns about his anxieties and regrets. <br /><br />Because it's stream of consciousness, it was sometimes easy to lose the flow, especially if my own thoughts were rambling, so I frequently had to double-back and try to pick up the narrative where I had drifted off course. However, the prose is lovely and the stories are memorable, so I didn't mind the backtracking. Highly recommended for readers who like literary fiction.</span>
